This project is aimed at investigating how trees and other vegetation use and cycle metals from soils in a temperate watershed in Pennsylvania. Depth profiles of metal concentrations were measured in the Pennsylvania soils at Penn State in collaboration with the lead investigator at Princeton University. Analysis of the profileds show that some metals such as molbydenum are enriched in the upper soil layers, while others are depleted. Two competing hypotheses are being tested to account for the high metal concentrations in the top soil layers. The first hypothesis suggests that  large atmospheric inputs from anthropogenic activities have caused the characteristic profiles in the soils. The second hypothesis is that metals are taken up into the trees (biological uplift) and then lost back to the soils as leaves fall to the ground and decay, enriching the topmost soils. Systematic analyses of green and senescent leaves, leaf litter and soils have been completed to unravel this question. Metals such as manganese appear to have been enriched in the soils due to anthropogenic inputs from coal burning, iron furnaces, and steel-making, both nearby and to the west of the watershed, while other metals show evidence of strictly biological uplift.

